question:
Find $a$ such that the matrix $\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 2 & 3 \\ 
4 & 5 & 6 \\ 
3 & 2 & a \end{array}
\right)$ is singular.

answer1:
$\begin{cases}
x(t) = c_1e^{t}-\frac{c_2}{3}e^{-2t} \\
y(t) = c_2e^{-2t}
\end{cases}$, where $c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}$.

answer2:
$\begin{cases}
x(t) = c_1e^{t}-\frac{c_2}{3}e^{-2t} \\
y(t) = c_1e^{t}+c_2e^{-2t}
\end{cases}$, where $c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}$.

answer3:
$\begin{cases}
x(t) = c_1e^{t}-\frac{c_2}{3}e^{-3t} \\
y(t) = c_2e^{-2t}
\end{cases}$, where $c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}$.

answer4:
$\begin{cases}
x(t) = c_1e^{-t}-\frac{c_2}{3}e^{2t} \\
y(t) = c_2e^{2t}
\end{cases}$, where $c_1, c_2 \in \mathbb{R}$.

